vllm-gfx1201
============

This project packages and lightly extends a large body of other people's work.
It would not exist without the following. Please preserve this NOTICE and the
upstream licenses in any redistribution.

The ONLY original contributions in this repository are:
  - the native HIP compute kernels — GDN (gdn_hip/), attention decode +
    paged prefill (attn_decode/, attn_prefill_paged/), ZAYA CCA (zaya/cca_hip/),
    and the W4A8-FP8-WMMA MoE kernel (w4a8_fp8_wmma/) — framework-agnostic
    torch.ops extensions co-developed with, and shared by, the sibling
    minisgl-rdna4 project. These now carry the heavy compute and superseded the
    earlier aiter / flash-attention / Composable-Kernel path (a dead end here).
  - the gfx1201 (RDNA4) vLLM platform-enablement edits, and
  - the Docker build/inject packaging and compose profiles.
Everything else is upstream, credited below.

Upstream projects and people
----------------------------
- The base image — tcclaviger/vllm22:dev (@tcclaviger): the vLLM 0.22.69 serving
  engine, the RDNA4 (gfx1201) runtime (ROCm 7.2.1, torch 2.10, Python 3.12), and
  the RXF ("Rotated eXtra Fast") W4A8 quant path — int8×int8 with an IQ4-NL
  codebook + FWHT-32 activation rotation — which still ships directly from
  upstream, unmodified by us. The combined image is `FROM` this base and runs
  vLLM's engine and scheduler; the attention / GDN / CCA compute now runs through
  our native HIP kernels (above) rather than the base's attention/GEMM backends.
- vLLM — vllm-project/vllm (Apache-2.0). The serving engine, shipped by the base
  image (vLLM 0.22.69). Our changes are a small ROCm platform-enablement edit plus
  the moe_wna16 tp_size fix (a generic upstream bug — owed back as a PR; see
  patches/upstream/). Thanks to @micah and the ROCm vLLM team.
- mini-SGLang / SGLang (sgl-project) — the serving-systems design lineage the
  sibling minisgl-rdna4 project draws on, and the context in which the shared
  native HIP kernels were developed. See docs/MINISGLANG_PATHWAYS.md.
- AMD aiter (ROCm/aiter, MIT/Apache), Dao-AILab flash-attention
  (Dao-AILab/flash-attention, BSD-3-Clause) and ROCm Composable Kernel
  (ROCm/composable_kernel, MIT, the CK FMHA backend) — evaluated as the
  attention/GEMM backends, but the shipped path moved to our native HIP kernels
  and no longer uses them. Kept for credit/history. The five A8W8 GEMM config
  JSONs from @carhuang's `carhuang/gfx1201_silu_and_mul_and_a8w8_configs_rebased`
  branch informed the early tuning. Thanks to @tridao.
- AMD ROCm / TheRock — the base of the *retired* wheel-distribution path, which
  built three gfx1201 wheels (vLLM / aiter / flash-attention) from source against
  AMD's TheRock (rocm/vllm-dev:nightly-therock714, ROCm 7.14) and the torch/triton
  nightlies. That path is archived on `archive/aiter-wheel-distribution`; the
  current stack no longer uses it (the base image above supersedes it).
- tilelang — the Qwen3_5Moe linear-attention (MHC) kernel path (upstream
  integration PR #43679).
- @kyuz0 — prior gfx1201 vLLM / ROCm-on-RDNA4 containers and PRs (e.g. the ViT
  attention-backend fix) that informed this enablement.
- cyankiwi — the AWQ-INT4 quantized models we run and benchmark
  (Qwen3.6-35B-A3B-AWQ-4bit, Mellum2-12B-A2.5B). The Qwen team for the base
  models.
- The gfx1151 sibling project (vllm-awq4-qwen) — the repository structure,
  compose, and README template, and the RDNA3.5 wave32 kernel-design lineage the
  W4A8 kernel was scaffolded from.
